## Phase 2 -- OSINT Reconnaissance (10 Checks)

Passive information gathering. No active probing. All 10 checks are independent -- one failure never stops the others.

### [1/10] WHOIS Lookup
Calls `python-whois` against the public WHOIS database. Extracts registrar, dates, nameservers, and registrant org. Domains expiring within 90 days raise a finding -- domain hijacking risk.

### [2/10] DNS Enumeration
Queries A, MX, TXT, NS, and CNAME records using `8.8.8.8` and `1.1.1.1` as fallback nameservers to avoid ISP DNS timeouts. Separately queries `_dmarc.target.com` -- if missing raises an email spoofing finding. Private IPs (RFC1918) are skipped automatically.

### [3/10] Subdomain Discovery
Two sources simultaneously. `crt.sh` certificate transparency logs reveal subdomains from every SSL cert ever issued. Then 90 common subdomain names are probed asynchronously (10 concurrent connections, HTTPS first then HTTP fallback). Sensitive subdomains (admin, staging, dev, git, jenkins) are auto-elevated to HIGH.

### [4/10] Google Dorking
Runs 20 pre-built dorks: exposed documents, admin panels, config files, API endpoints, sensitive strings. Anti-detection via rotating user agents and random jitter. Google blocks automation quickly -- R3D detects 429 and switches automatically to DuckDuckGo for remaining dorks.

### [5/10] Wayback Machine
Queries archive.org CDX API for up to 500 historical URLs. Checks each for sensitive keywords: admin, login, api, config, backup, .env, .git, password, secret, token. Historical endpoints may still be live. Private IPs are skipped automatically.

### [6/10] Tech Stack Detection
One HTTP request (HTTPS first, HTTP fallback). WAF detection runs first against 8 vendor signatures. Then checks 15 tech signatures against the full response. Server header read for version disclosure. Missing security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy) each become findings. Duplicate suppression: tech already reported in server header is not re-created from HTML fingerprint.

### [7/10] AI Surface Detection
Probes 30 endpoint signatures. GET first -- 404 means skip. Then POST confirmation with JSON body. Returns JSON or 401/403/405 = confirmed LLM API. Returns HTML = login redirect = not a real LLM, skipped. This two-step process eliminates false positives from routers and login pages.

### [8/10] Email Harvesting
Scrapes 10 public pages plus top 5 subdomains. Regex finds email addresses matching target domain. Filters generic addresses (noreply, support, info, admin). Real employee emails extracted -- usernames queued for Sherlock.

### [9/10] Breach Checking
HIBP checks each harvested email against known breaches (requires paid API key, skips cleanly without). GitHub search runs 5 queries looking for repositories that accidentally committed credentials containing the target domain.

### [10/10] Sherlock Username Enumeration
Runs `sherlock-project` via subprocess against 300+ platforms. Hard rules: never in FULL-AUTO, separate explicit consent required, max 5 usernames, 60 second timeout each, input sanitized before passing.

