## Phase 4 -- Traditional Reconnaissance (8 Checks)

### [1-3/8] Port Scan + Service Detection + CVE Correlation
Three steps in one Nmap call. Port scan finds open ports (top 1000 default, all 65535 with `--full-scan`). Service detection identifies what is running and what version. CVE correlation searches the local 295,406-entry NVD database per versioned service. Unmatched services flagged as potential zero day candidates.

### [4/8] SSL/TLS Audit
Checks protocol versions (TLS 1.0 and 1.1 flagged deprecated), certificate expiry, issuer, hostname mismatch, and cipher suite weakness.

### [5/8] Security Headers
Six critical headers checked: HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy. Each missing header becomes its own finding.

### [6/8] Endpoint Discovery
49 common paths probed: admin panels, API endpoints, sensitive files (.env, .git, backup.zip, db.sql), debug interfaces. Non-404 response = finding. High-value paths auto-elevated to HIGH.

### [7/8] JavaScript Bundle Analysis
Downloads JS files and parses with regex patterns: AWS keys (AKIA pattern), API tokens, database connection strings, internal URLs, password variables. Developers frequently leave credentials hardcoded from development in production JS bundles.

### [8/8] WAF Bypass Attempt
Only runs if OSINT detected a WAF. Sends X-Forwarded-For and X-Real-IP headers, checks DNS history for origin IP exposure, compares WAF vs origin response content. Bypass confirmed = real attack surface accessible without WAF protection.

